Believers in free trade
From Cambridge — Recently, I was invited to guest-lecture in the globalization course of two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you," I said.
One of them had warned me in advance: "These students are all strong supporters of globalization."
In the first class, he once asked the students present to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90% favored the former.
And this is even before we have begun to teach the amazing effects of comparative advantage.
We know that using the same questions to survey a representative sample in a real investigation — rather than Harvard students — would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers of Harvard students would not be particularly surprising.
Because people with higher technical skills and better education tend to support free trade more than blue-collar workers.
Perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their future (financial) prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they simply don't understand how trade actually works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different form and emphasized the distributional effects that trade might generate.
The consensus in favor of fair trade completely disappeared, even more swiftly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked everyone if they agreed to a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account disappear—poof!—while simultaneously adding $300 to John's account. Through the great feat of social engineering, this class as a whole would gain an additional $100 in value.
Then would they allow me to play this little trick?
The result showed that only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.
Sure, please provide the sentence you would like translated from Chinese to English.
It is obviously difficult for students to tolerate such a form of significant income redistribution, even if the overall economic pie has been greatly expanded.
I then asked why most of them almost instinctively supported free trade, even though free trade itself would also lead to a similar — indeed, even a more significant — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students all looked stunned.
I continued, let's assume that Nicholas and John each started a small competing company.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced better products. As a result, he not only had $300 more than Nicholas but also drove Nicholas's company out of the market, causing Nicholas a loss of $200.
So how many students support this change?
This time, the majority voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I immediately proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
If John is driving Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or outsource business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or is it employing child labor in Indonesia?
The level of agreement with this change decreases sequentially with the aforementioned options.
In addition, technological innovation can also leave certain groups in a more vulnerable position, just as trade does. What is your view on this?
Very few students are willing to restrain the development of technology.
It's a ridiculous idea to ban the production of light bulbs in order to save the jobs of candle makers for almost everyone.
Therefore, students may not necessarily oppose redistribution itself, but only certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they also care about the fairness of the procedure.
If we are to judge the results of redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that produced such results.
We do not resent Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even though some of their competitors have had a tough time, probably because they and their competitors all operate according to the same fundamental rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become rich not through their own intelligence and hard work, but through fraud, violation of labor laws, environmental destruction, or by taking advantage of subsidies from foreign governments, our opinion would be entirely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved by violating widely accepted domestic moral standards, then on what grounds can we feel at ease simply because it involves international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect that redistribution effects will eventually lead to equality in the long run and that everyone will ultimately benefit, we are likely to care less about the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that despite the short-term negative reactions that technology may bring to some people, we are still willing to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group of people — low-educated blue-collar workers — we once again become deeply concerned about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute their worries about globalization to foolish, self-centered protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
These economists are also unable to properly engage in public discourse because they cannot recognize that international trade, although not often, sometimes leads to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically.
And if they themselves are morally indefensible, how can they strongly advocate for trade?
When globalization occasionally raises thorny issues related to the legitimacy of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond by restricting trade.
There are still many pros and cons that need to be carefully weighed, including the possibility that globalization may cause greater wealth deprivation for people in other parts of the world than for American victims themselves.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this issue and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions as a result.
However, the obsession with globalization merely because it has made the cake bigger will inevitably erode its own legitimacy in the long run.
